    "content": "<p>Find out the wrong number.</p>\n<p>2, 6, 12, 72, 865, 62208</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "72"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "12"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "62208"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "865"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>To find the wrong number in the sequence, we need to look for some pattern that the other numbers follow which the wrong number does not. Let's examine the sequence given:</p>\n\n<p>2, 6, 12, 72, 865, 62208</p>\n\n<p>At first glance, there doesn't seem to be a simple arithmetic progression or geometric progression. Therefore, we need to look for alternative patterns. One method is to examine the ratios of successive terms to see if they follow a certain pattern:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>6 / 2 = 3</li>\n<li>12 / 6 = 2</li>\n<li>72 / 12 = 6</li>\n<li>865 / 72 ≈ 12.01</li>\n<li>62208 / 865 ≈ 71.91</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The pattern isn't immediately clear from these ratios. Another approach is to look at how each number could be generated from the previous one using any mathematical operations (such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, powers, factorials, etc.). A more complex pattern may involve factorials or powers, given how the numbers increase rapidly. But looking at the jumps between the numbers, another idea might be to examine multiplicative factors increased by non-constant additive increments:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>The jump from 2 to 6 is by multiplying by 3 (2 * 3).</li>\n<li>The jump from 6 to 12 is by multiplying by 2 (6 * 2).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the pattern is based on multiplying by natural numbers and each time we increase the multiplier by 1, we would expect:</p>\n\n<p>2 (multiplied by 3) = 6</p>\n<p>6 (multiplied by 2) = 12</p>\n<p>12 (multiplied by 3) should be 36, but we have 72.</p>\n\n<p>At this stage, there is a clear discrepancy since 72 is not obtainable by multiplying 12 by 3. Let's continue to see if there is a different pattern:</p>\n\n<p>12 (multiplied by 6) = 72</p>\n<p>72 (multiplied by 12) = 864</p>\n\n<p>According to the second part of the pattern, the term after 72 should be 864 if we multiply by 12. But instead, we have 865. This suggests that 865 is the number that does not fit in the pattern. We would expect a multiplication sequence by consecutive natural numbers (2, 3, 4, ...) or some similar pattern. Either way, 865 is incorrect because it is one more than what the pattern suggests (864).</p>\n\n<p>Given the choices:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Option A: 72 - This fits with our pattern when using a multiplier of 6.</li>\n<li>Option B: 12 - This fits with our pattern when using a multiplier of 2.</li>\n<li>Option C: 62208 - It doesn’t fit the pattern if we extend it, but keep in mind 865 is already incorrect and should be 864.</li>\n<li>Option D: 865 - This number is one more than what the pattern suggests, so it is the incorrect number in the sequence.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Therefore, the answer is:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option D: 865</strong></p>",
